fields.title: Phonemes
fields.short:
Phonemes - one or several letters which form one sound:

ch- cheese, b - ball, s - student, sh- sheep, etc.

fields.title: Noun
fields.full:
A noun is a word that refers to a thing (book), a person (Betty Crocker), an animal (cat), a place (Omaha), a quality (softness), an idea (justice), or an action (listening).

It's usually a single word, but not always: cake, shoes, school bus, and time and a half are all nouns.

fields.title: Pronoun
fields.short: Pronouns stand for a person or a thing: I, you, he, she, it, we, you, they

fields.title: Singular and Plural Nouns
fields.short:
Singular (one): dog, boy, shirt

Plural (many): dogs, boys, shirts

Exceptions: man/men, mouse/mice, etc.
fields.full:
We add "s" or "es" to a noun:

cat => cats

sandwich => sandwiches
fields.fullest: We use these rules for plural nouns:

fields.title: Adjective
fields.short:
Adjectives describe qualities, states of nouns: good, bad, yellow, fun, fast, etc.

They can also describe the quantity (number) of nouns: one, two, many, some, etc.
fields.full:
Adjetives usually go before nouns:

Beautiful house, fat cat
